The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, March 26, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		A middle-aged man, Samir Das, was arrested from Jadavpur on Thursday for fabricating a story of kidnapping and misleading the police. According to police, Das telephoned his house in Bagha Jatin saying that he had been kidnapped and would not be released till his family paid up Rs 20,000. His wife Manju went to the police station and sought help to rescue her husband. After tracking down the number from which Das call had come, police came to know that the call was made from a neighbours house. Das was picked up from there. During interrogation, he revealed that he had made the call himself.																																																		The high court on Thursday ruled that the municipalities and corporations had no right to sanction the plan of a building submitted by developers if the owner of the land was the applicant. While disposing of a petition by a landowner, the high court judge asked the municipality to sanction the plan submitted by the petitioner.																																																		A division bench of Calcutta High Court on Thursday rejected the bail petition of Basudev Mondal of Murshidabad, who was sentenced to 10 years rigorous imprisonment by a sessions judge for cohabiting with a woman after giving her false assurances of marriage. While delivering the order, the judges said that the accused in such cases should get exemplary punishment.																																																		The state cabinet on Thursday congratulated captain Sourav Ganguly and his teammates on Indias victory at Lahore. The cabinet noted that ties between the people of the two countries had been strengthened through the series.																																																		Trouble broke out at Kajipara, Kajidanga, in the Shibpur police station area in Howrah, after Calcutta Electric Supply Corporation employees went to disconnect unauthorised electric connections in some residential buildings. According to police, local residents protested against CESCs action and claimed that the connections were authorised. Police reached the spot and brought the situation under control. No arrest was made.																																																		The Howrah Municipal Corporation (HMC) has ordered the Howrah Animal Welfare Organisation to shift from Ram Charan Chatterjee Lane in the Shibpur police station area. The order was passed after receiving a complaint from residents that the organisation was breaking peace in the area. HMC mayor Gopal Mukherjee asked the organisation to shift from the residential area.																																																		The Howrah District Youth Congress has filed a petition with the road transport officer of Howrah to ply buses on the Alampur-Dunlop route. 							TO GLRA India and the state health department for screening Phera, a film on tuberculosis, and organising a program-me to increase awareness about the disease 
